In this step, we're going to develop a schedule.

2
00:00:04.884 --> 00:00:10.011
Now the WBS by itself is not a schedule, it is merely a list of tasks.

3
00:00:10.011 --> 00:00:10.284
Okay,

4
00:00:10.284 --> 00:00:13.830
so the project schedule will have a start and end date for each

5
00:00:13.830 --> 00:00:16.473
and every task that you have on the plan,

6
00:00:16.473 --> 00:00:22.011
and when you have some prerequisites for this as well of course.

7
00:00:22.011 --> 00:00:28.011
The WBS, of course, that's the list of all the tasks to complete the project.

8
00:00:28.011 --> 00:00:30.234
Resources assigned, what are all the resources needed?

9
00:00:30.234 --> 00:00:32.178
Now these are usually people of course,

10
00:00:32.178 --> 00:00:36.611
but it could also be tools or other sort of physical artifacts.

11
00:00:36.611 --> 00:00:41.011
We want the estimate for every task, the amount of time,

12
00:00:41.011 --> 00:00:43.538
preferably in hours, I don't really like days,

13
00:00:43.538 --> 00:00:47.011
or weeks, or months, let's get more specific and use hours.

14
00:00:47.011 --> 00:00:48.485
Next, the confidence factor,

15
00:00:48.485 --> 00:00:52.169
this'll help you keep your eye on the task that

16
00:00:52.169 --> 00:00:54.380
you're not quite that confident in,

17
00:00:54.380 --> 00:00:58.064
in either the hours estimate or maybe some other factors.

18
00:00:58.064 --> 00:01:01.011
This'll help you later focus on improving the

19
00:01:01.011 --> 00:01:03.364
elements about this particular task.

20
00:01:03.364 --> 00:01:06.188
And lastly, task relationships or dependencies,

21
00:01:06.188 --> 00:01:11.761
does task A have to be done before say task B?

22
00:01:11.761 --> 00:01:17.261
Now Microsoft Project and other tools are very good at

23
00:01:17.261 --> 00:01:20.011
defining and tracking task dependencies.

24
00:01:20.011 --> 00:01:26.011
Okay, now let's take a look at an example.

25
00:01:26.011 --> 00:01:27.761
Here is our familiar example.

