I just took the earliest start date and the latest end date,

44
00:02:35.801 --> 00:02:38.011
and that basically is my entire range.

45
00:02:38.011 --> 00:02:40.761
Now of course other tools like Microsoft Project may come in

46
00:02:40.761 --> 00:02:43.835
very handy or easier if your project is more complicated with

47
00:02:43.835 --> 00:02:48.776
dependencies that are even larger, but I found for projects maybe 2,

48
00:02:48.776 --> 00:02:51.511
3, 4 people, using a spreadsheet is just very,

49
00:02:51.511 --> 00:02:55.011
very easy to come up with a very quick and actually quite accurate schedule

50
00:02:55.011 --> 00:02:57.854
to share back with your customer or your stakeholders.

51
00:02:57.854 --> 00:03:07.011
Now let me share with you some scheduling tips to help you do your scheduling.

52
00:03:07.011 --> 00:03:07.364
Okay,

53
00:03:07.364 --> 00:03:10.188
I recommend strongly that your scheduling process must

54
00:03:10.188 --> 00:03:14.261
cover all of the work on the project, not just some of it.

55
00:03:14.261 --> 00:03:17.261
A lot of the times things get left off like quality assurance,

56
00:03:17.261 --> 00:03:20.636
or promoting software from DEV to QA to production,

57
00:03:20.636 --> 00:03:25.011
documentation, release notes, it's everything you could possibly think of,

58
00:03:25.011 --> 00:03:27.482
everything you can possibly think of, meetings,

59
00:03:27.482 --> 00:03:29.247
time to write status reports,

60
00:03:29.247 --> 00:03:33.511
etc., to cover everything to get a more accurate estimate.

61
00:03:33.511 --> 00:03:38.011
Also be as realistic as possible, what is reality,

62
00:03:38.011 --> 00:03:41.011
you know the people, you know their strengths.

63
00:03:41.011 --> 00:03:44.272
A lot of times though, you do get a lot of pressure from senior management,

64
00:03:44.272 --> 00:03:46.011
I want this done by a certain date.

65
00:03:46.011 --> 00:03:49.396
You need to have the strength and the integrity to say,

66
00:03:49.396 --> 00:03:54.011
hey, this is what it's really going to take to go do for our team.

67
00:03:54.011 --> 00:03:55.511
Also do a sanity check.

68
00:03:55.511 --> 00:04:00.011
You might think your schedule looks pretty good, but can you really get it done?

69
00:04:00.011 --> 00:04:03.067
Make sure you've talked to the right people on your team,

70
00:04:03.067 --> 00:04:03.900
maybe stakeholders, customers,

71
00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:09.011
or other mentors in your company to make sure that those

72
00:04:09.011 --> 00:04:13.011
estimates and the scheduling dates are realistic.

73
00:04:13.011 --> 00:04:15.466
And also have buy in from the project team.

74
00:04:15.466 --> 00:04:18.193
If someone says there's no way I can do this,

75
00:04:18.193 --> 00:04:21.070
they will feel that way throughout the software development process,

76
00:04:21.070 --> 00:04:24.011
and just won't be as much of a team player,

77
00:04:24.011 --> 00:04:27.931
or won't have as much faith or respect in you as a project manager,

78
00:04:27.931 --> 00:04:31.011
you really want to get the buy in of your team.

79
00:04:31.011 --> 00:04:34.011
And lastly of course, everything must be documented,

80
00:04:34.011 --> 00:04:36.636
communicated to the team on your project,

81
00:04:36.636 --> 00:04:38.956
stakeholders, and I think updated weekly,

82
00:04:38.956 --> 00:04:42.845
in other words, things change, the estimates might get higher,

83
00:04:42.845 --> 00:04:46.070
they might get lower, when the estimates change,

84
00:04:46.070 --> 00:04:51.011
the schedule will change, so I revisit and update my project schedule,

85
00:04:51.011 --> 00:04:51.726
and estimates,

86
00:04:51.726 --> 00:04:56.011
and tasks every single week on every single project to be accurate.

